Understanding the /pol/tards Brain

It doesn’t matter how smart /pol/tards are or how well they scored on the SAT or ACT. Good judgment isn’t something they can excel in, at least not yet.

The rational part of a /pol/tard’s brain isn’t fully developed and won’t be until age 25 or so.

In fact, recent research has found that adult and /pol/tards brains work differently. Adults think with the prefrontal cortex, the brain’s rational part. This is the part of the brain that responds to situations with good judgment and an awareness of long-term consequences. /pol/tards process information with the amygdala. This is the emotional part.

In /pol/tards' brains, the connections between the emotional part of the brain and the decision-making center are still developing—and not always at the same rate. That’s why when poltards have overwhelming emotional input, they can’t explain later what they were thinking. They weren’t thinking as much as they were feeling.

A poltard’s Brain Isn’t Fully Developed Until Age 25

Even though your poltard is now as tall as you are it doesn’t mean that they have fully matured. Even though your poltard may score high on the SAT or the ACT, it’s important to remember that a poltard’s brain is still under development. In fact, if your poltard is a teenager, then you can bet that parts of their brain still need to grow and mature. For instance, there are obvious differences between the brains of adults and trad larpers indicating that change, maturity, and transformation are still underway in poltards.

Brains of Young /pol/tards Not Fully Mature

At an age when /pol/tards are first considered adults, their brains are still maturing, a new study suggests.


"The brain of an 18-year-old college /pol/tard is still far from resembling the brain of someone in their mid-twenties," said Craig Bennett, a graduate student who was involved in the new research.
